<p style=3D'margin:0in;font-family:Calibri;font-size:11.0pt'>Step: Rank + P=
ER</p>

<p style=3D'margin:0in;font-family:Calibri;font-size:11.0pt'>Action: Sustai=
ned</p>

<p style=3D'margin:0in;font-family:Calibri;font-size:11.0pt'>&nbsp;</p>

<p style=3D'margin:0in;font-family:Calibri;font-size:11.0pt'>With this powe=
r,
Horrors can create Horror constructs from other life forms such as mundane
animals, magical creatures, and even Namegivers. Horrors can forge construc=
ts
from dead or living bodies, although they prefer living creatures. When usi=
ng
Namegivers, the vilest Horrors usually leave a bit of the victim’s mind i=
ntact,
so that he will live out his entire existence dimly aware that he is a Horr=
or
construct. To use this power against living targets, the Horror must have
previously Horror-marked them. The body used must be of sufficient size and
weight to form the body of the construct desired. For example, a Horror wou=
ld
need a body at least the size of troll or obsidiman to create a construct as
large as a jehuthra. However, as Horror constructs can be of virtually any =
size
and shape, most Horrors can make do with whatever victims happen to be hand=
y.</p>

<p style=3D'margin:0in;font-family:Calibri;font-size:11.0pt'>&nbsp;</p>

<p style=3D'margin:0in;font-family:Calibri;font-size:11.0pt'>To forge a con=
struct
costs the Horror 5 points of Karma. These initial Karma Points infuse the
target body with the Horror’s magical energy, initiating the body’s
transformation. After the Horror has initiated the change, it makes a serie=
s of
five Forge Horror Construct Tests against the target body’s Spell Defense=
. If
the target body is dead, use the Spell Defense the target had when it was
alive. Each successful Forge Horror Construct Test allows the Horror to alt=
er
one of the target body’s Attributes to that of the type of construct being
forged or to grant the construct a power or special ability. Each result le=
vel
above Average on any Forge Horror Construct Test allows the Horror to alter=
 one
additional Attribute or add one additional power. Note that the Horror cann=
ot
add his Karma dice to the roll for any of these tests; the Karma is used si=
mply
to fuel the power.</p>

<p style=3D'margin:0in;font-family:Calibri;font-size:11.0pt'>&nbsp;</p>

<p style=3D'margin:0in;font-family:Calibri;font-size:11.0pt'>The Horror can=
 also
alter the target’s other characteristics by 1 point for every additional =
point
of Karma spent. When spending Karma to change a certain Characteristic, the
Horror makes an additional Forge Horror Construct Test. There is no limit t=
o the
number of additional Karma Points a Horror can spend on forging a construct.
For example, if a Horror spends 2 Karma Points to grow natural armor on his
victim, he needs to succeed at a Forge Horror Construct Test against the
victim’s Spell Defense. As a result, the victim’s skin hardens permanen=
tly,
providing 2 points of natural Armor.</p>

<p style=3D'margin:0in;font-family:Calibri;font-size:11.0pt'>&nbsp;</p>

<p style=3D'margin:0in;font-family:Calibri;font-size:11.0pt'>When used agai=
nst
living targets, each successful Forge Horror Construct Test causes damage to
the victim equal to the result of the test. This damage often kills the tar=
get,
but many Horrors make a point of leaving the target an alive and unwilling =
pawn
in their control. To alter the Attributes of living targets, the Horror must
achieve a Good result on its Forge Horror Construct Tests. When a Horror us=
es
this power against Namegivers, the victim may make a Willpower Test to atte=
mpt
to resist the effects of the Horror’s magic. The result of the Willpower =
Test
can substitute for the victim’s Spell Defense when he resists in this way=
. Then
the victim makes a Willpower Test for each of the Horror’s Forge Horror
Construct Tests. If the result of the victim’s Willpower Test is lower th=
an his
Spell Defense, he defends using his normal Spell Defense.</p>

<p style=3D'margin:0in;font-family:Calibri;font-size:11.0pt'>&nbsp;</p>

<p style=3D'margin:0in;font-family:Calibri;font-size:11.0pt'>When all the
construct’s Attributes and abilities have been altered as the Horror wish=
es,
the Horror makes a Horror Mark Test to form a link between itself and the
construct. If this test succeeds, the construct is complete. Once formed,
Horror constructs remain under the control of the Horror that forged them. =
Many
Horrors forge constructs and let them roam Barsaive, inflicting pain and
suffering on all the Namegivers they encounter. Almost all magically active
Horrors possess the ability to forge constructs. The Horror powers Animate =
Dead
and Karma Tap are specialized forms of this power, each with special
restrictions. Dual-natured Horrors can also use this power to forge new bod=
ies
for themselves, and some Horrors build this power into Horror-cursed items.
When activated, such items begin to transform a victim into a construct as
described above.</p>

<p style=3D'margin:0in;font-family:Calibri;font-size:11.0pt'>&nbsp;</p>

<p style=3D'margin:0in;font-family:Calibri;font-size:11.0pt'>This ability is
extremely powerful, and gamemasters should use it sparingly against player
characters.</p>

