rd</p>

<p style=3D'margin:0in;font-family:Calibri;font-size:11.0pt'>&nbsp;</p>

<p style=3D'margin:0in;font-family:Calibri;font-size:11.0pt'>The Forge Trap=
 power
enables a Horror to transform an earth, stone, or metal passageway so that =
it
becomes a trap or contains one. The nature of the Horror determines the pre=
cise
type of trap. The Difficulty Number for the Forge Trap Test necessary to use
this power is based on the predominant material of the passageway. For a
passage of raw earth, the Difficulty Number is 6; for raw stone, 10; for wo=
rked
stone, 15; and for metal, 20. If the Forge Trap Test succeeds, distribute t=
he
result between the trap’s Detection Difficulty, Disarm Difficulty, Trap
Initiative, and Trap Effect/Damage Step. See Traps in the Adventuring chapt=
er
on p. 110 for more information on traps and how they work.</p>

<p style=3D'margin:0in;font-family:Calibri;font-size:11.0pt'>&nbsp;</p>

<p style=3D'margin:0in;font-family:Calibri;font-size:11.0pt'>The Horror may=
 spend
a Karma Point to create a link between itself and its traps, which enables =
it
to use the Energy Drain power to feed on the suffering of any living being
taking damage from the traps. Traps may do indirect damage—for example, by
preventing characters from escaping a small room—and may require nonstand=
ard
methods to neutralize. For example, characters might need to solve a riddle=
 or
puzzle to deactivate the trap.</p>

