<div style=3D'direction:ltr;margin-top:0in;margin-left:0in;width:1.1034in'>

<p style=3D'margin:0in;font-family:Calibri;font-size:17.0pt'>Spells</p>

</div>

<div style=3D'direction:ltr;margin-top:.4506in;margin-left:0in;width:7.5048=
in'>

<p style=3D'margin:0in;font-family:Calibri;font-size:11.0pt'>CREATURE SPELL=
S</p>

<p style=3D'margin:0in;font-family:Calibri;font-size:11.0pt'>Step Number: S=
pecial
(see text)</p>

<p style=3D'margin:0in;font-family:Calibri;font-size:11.0pt'>Action: NA</p>

<p style=3D'margin:0in;font-family:Calibri;font-size:11.0pt'>Type: Magical<=
/p>

<p style=3D'margin:0in;font-family:Calibri;font-size:11.0pt'>&nbsp;</p>

<p style=3D'margin:0in;font-family:Calibri;font-size:11.0pt'>Generally, cre=
atures
can cast spells of only one Discipline, though some powerful creatures are =
able
to cast spells of several Disciplines. The spells that the creature can cast
are listed with its description.</p>

<p style=3D'margin:0in;font-family:Calibri;font-size:11.0pt'>&nbsp;</p>

<p style=3D'margin:0in;font-family:Calibri;font-size:11.0pt'>DRAGON SPELLS<=
/p>

<p style=3D'margin:0in;font-family:Calibri;font-size:11.0pt'>Step: Special =
(see
text)</p>

<p style=3D'margin:0in;font-family:Calibri;font-size:11.0pt'>Action: NA</p>

<p style=3D'margin:0in;font-family:Calibri;font-size:11.0pt'>&nbsp;</p>

<p style=3D'margin:0in;font-family:Calibri;font-size:11.0pt'>Dragons are na=
tural
born spellcasters, with an inherent knowledge of the workings of magic. They
use spell magic regularly. This power refers to the dragon’s use of spell=
 magic
as practiced by magician adepts (spell matrices, threads, etc.), but dragon=
s also
have their own unique form of spell magic.</p>

<p style=3D'margin:0in;font-family:Calibri;font-size:11.0pt'>&nbsp;</p>

<p style=3D'margin:0in;font-family:Calibri;font-size:11.0pt'>HORROR SPELLS<=
/p>

<p style=3D'margin:0in;font-family:Calibri;font-size:11.0pt'>Step: Special =
(see
text)</p>

<p style=3D'margin:0in;font-family:Calibri;font-size:11.0pt'>Action: NA</p>

<p style=3D'margin:0in;font-family:Calibri;font-size:11.0pt'>&nbsp;</p>

<p style=3D'margin:0in;font-family:Calibri;font-size:11.0pt'>Horrors often =
learn
spells from sentient captives who follow a particular magician Discipline.
Horrors can learn every spell from their captives’ listed Disciplines and
Circles, though they rarely learn those spells that affect the undead and
spirits. Though Horrors may learn the spells from a Discipline, they acquire
none of that Discipline’s other talents.</p>

<p style=3D'margin:0in;font-family:Calibri;font-size:11.0pt'>&nbsp;</p>

<p style=3D'margin:0in;font-family:Calibri;font-size:11.0pt'>SPIRIT
SPELLS<br>
Step: Special (see text)</p>

<p style=3D'margin:0in;font-family:Calibri;font-size:11.0pt'>Action: NA</p>

<p style=3D'margin:0in;font-family:Calibri;font-size:11.0pt'>Elemental spir=
its
may only cast spells that deal with their native elements. Generally, ally
spirits can cast spells of only one Discipline, though some powerful ally
spirits can cast spells of several Disciplines. The spirit’s Strength Rat=
ing
determines the maximum spell Circle it may cast. Thus, a Strength 6 ally sp=
irit
could cast any spell up to Sixth Circle for any type of magic it knows.</p>

</div>

</div>

</div>

<p style=3D'margin:0in'>&nbsp;</p>

<p style=3D'margin:0in'>&nbsp;</p>

<p style=3D'margin:0in'>&nbsp;</p>

<div style=3D'direction:ltr;border-width:100%'>

<div style=3D'direction:ltr;margin-top:0in;margin-left:0in;width:7.5715in'>

<div style=3D'direction:ltr;margin-top:0in;margin-left:0in;width:1.6451in'>

<p style=3D'margin:0in;font-family:Calibri;font-size:17.0pt'>Sticky Body</p>

</div>

<div style=3D'direction:ltr;margin-top:.45in;margin-left:0in;width:7.5715in=
'>

<p style=3D'margin:0in;font-family:Calibri;font-size:11.0pt'>Step Number: R=
ank +
WIL</p>

<p style=3D'margin:0in;font-family:Calibri;font-size:11.0pt'>Action: Free</=
p>

<p style=3D'margin:0in;font-family:Calibri;font-size:11.0pt'>Type: Magical;
Mundane</p>

<p style=3D'margin:0in;font-family:Calibri;font-size:11.0pt'>&nbsp;</p>

<p style=3D'margin:0in;font-family:Calibri;font-size:11.0pt'>Water. Creatur=
es
with this power excrete a sticky fluid. Whenever the creature comes into
contact with another character or item, the creature makes a Sticky Body Te=
st
against the target’s Spell Defense. If the test is successful, the fluid =
glues
the character and the creature together. Creatures using this ability are f=
ree
to perform other actions while attached to a victim. A character is conside=
red
Harried (Player’s Guide p. 227) as soon as even a single creature sticks =
to him
using this power. Once four creatures stick to a target, it begins to
suffocate. The victim takes 1 Damage Point each combat round until fewer th=
an
four creatures remain on it. No armor protects against this damage. Charact=
ers
suffer from being Overwhelmed (Player’s Guide p. 227) at this stage, furt=
her
hampering them. As a guideline, up to six creatures can stick to a characte=
r of
equal size. To break free from the gluey gob, the target must make a succes=
sful
Strength Test against the result of the creature’s Sticky Body Test. The =
only
other way to escape the glue is to wait for the sun to break down the
substance, but a creature with this power will rarely allow that to happen.
Making physical attacks against a sticky creature is very difficult. At the
start of combat, the gamemaster makes a Sticky Body Test to determine the
strength of the creature’s adhesive layer. Whenever an opponent successfu=
lly
attacks the creature, his weapon, hand and so on sticks to the creature; the
attacker must make a successful Strength Test against the result of the Sti=
cky
Body Test to pull the weapon or limb free. If the Strength Test fails, the
attacker may make further Strength Tests, but the Difficulty Number for each
additional test increases by +1.</p>

</div>

</div>

</div>

<p style=3D'margin:0in'>&nbsp;</p>

<p style=3D'margin:0in'>&nbsp;</p>

<p style=3D'margin:0in'>&nbsp;</p>

<div style=3D'direction:ltr;border-width:100%'>

<div style=3D'direction:ltr;margin-top:0in;margin-left:0in;width:7.6041in'>

<div style=3D'direction:ltr;margin-top:0in;margin-left:0in;width:1.527in'>

<p style=3D'margin:0in;font-family:Calibri;font-size:17.0pt'>Sticky Spit</p>

</div>

<div style=3D'direction:ltr;margin-top:.45in;margin-left:0in;width:7.6041in=
'>

<p style=3D'margin:0in;font-family:Calibri;font-size:11.0pt'>Step Number: R=
ank +
STR</p>

<p style=3D'margin:0in;font-family:Calibri;font-size:11.0pt'>Action: Standa=
rd</p>

<p style=3D'margin:0in;font-family:Calibri;font-size:11.0pt'>Type: Magical;
Mundane</p>

<p style=3D'margin:0in;font-family:Calibri;font-size:11.0pt'>&nbsp;</p>

<p style=3D'margin:0in;font-family:Calibri;font-size:11.0pt'>Water. Creatur=
es
using this power usually prefer to glue their foes to the ground rather than
fight them in close combat. The creature can spit a gob of adhesive at any
opponent within the range listed in its description. To spit the gob, the
creature makes a Sticky Spit Test against the target’s Physical Defense. =
The
power’s range is the creature’s Rank × 2 yards (1 hexes). If the test =
succeeds,
the target is struck by the mucus. The spit hinders the character’s movem=
ent;
the character is considered Harried (Player’s Guide p. 227). The spit can=
 be
removed with a mild acid, such as vinegar, and a good scrubbing brush.
Alternatively, a round spent trying to pull the goo free allows the target =
to
make a Strength Test against the creature’s Sticky Spit Test result. If t=
his
test succeeds, enough of the goo has been removed to allow freedom of movem=
ent
again. For this reason, it is common for creature with this power to use it
more than once against the same opponent to ensure its prey is well and tru=
ly
stuck (and to force multiple Strength Tests to break free). The gamemaster =
may
wish to use the Overwhelmed rule (Player’s Guide p. 227) to account for t=
he
effect of multiple Sticky Spit attacks on a target.</p>

</div>

</div>

</div>

